segments.text: Many of us here today don't need to ask the tough question, where will you lay your head to sleep tonight?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But for our neighbors sleeping under tents and cardboard and bushes, that's a question of life and death they have to ask every night.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We're here today to help answer that question for dozens of our neighbors experiencing homelessness.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: My name is Alex Peterson, the city council member for this district, and today we will answer with more than a message of hope.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Today we will answer with solid structures that people can count on to shelter them from the rain and from the despair in the face of homelessness.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Today is not a day for hand wringing or finger pointing.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Today is a day for results.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: More than 30 new houses.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: These houses may be tiny, but their impact is huge.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Houses built strong with wood and shingles and love.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Welcoming places for unsheltered neighbors to reset and renew.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Welcome to Rosie's Village.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Thank you to Sound Transit, the Low Income Housing Institute, City Hall, and the many U-District small businesses and neighbors who made it possible to open today.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: It's named for the adjacent street, Roosevelt Way, Northeast, and Rosie's Village will provide residents with professional case management, 24-7 security, kitchen and hygiene facilities.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Rosie's Village will empower people to obtain jobs and healthcare, food security, and ultimately permanent housing for a brighter life.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Like all of us here today, I've seen the urgent need to do more to respond to the crisis of homelessness during the crisis of COVID.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And the university district, like many neighborhoods across Seattle, has seen a disturbing increase in visible homelessness.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: As soon as this site became available here in our district, I reached out to Sound Transit to ask them, would they be willing to lease this land to the city?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Could we bring more people inside?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Sound Transit said yes.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So last year during the city's budget process, I secured the funding for construction and operations.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: When the project ran into a barrier of bureaucratic hurdles, we worked together to work around, jump over these hurdles.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: With Councilmember Lewis, he and I expedited the legislation to get it done.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And while one tiny home village is not going to solve the problem of homelessness, by opening Rosy's today, we can, like Teddy Roosevelt's niece Eleanor Roosevelt, light a candle rather than curse the darkness.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And this is one small bright spot to shine a beacon for other efforts that are bigger across the region.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And I want to thank everybody for being here today.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I'm going to turn it over now to the person who gets things done in the non-profit world in Seattle and beyond, Sharon Lee, Low Income Housing Institute.
